    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. it's definitely looking like nitrogen though, the yellowing is pretty widespread on the old leaves. if i want to fix the soil for them, what should i be looking at in terms of pH? i want to make sure they can actually absorb the nutrients i'm adding.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "For most tomatoes, an optimal soil pH range is between 6.0 and 6.8. If your pH is too high (alkaline), it can lock up essential micronutrients, making them unavailable even if they are present in the soil. You can test your soil with a simple test kit to determine your current pH level. Adjustments can be made using elemental sulfur to lower the pH or lime to raise it, depending on your readings.",
      "source": "target",
