    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "got it. so if the pH is off, it's basically like the nutrients are just sitting there and the plant can't reach them? feels like something is actively preventing the plant from getting what it needs even when i try to help. any other ways the soil environment might be \"stealing\" the nutrients away from the roots?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, an improper pH creates an impenetrable barrier, essentially making the nutrients biologically unavailable to the roots. Beyond pH, root rot caused by overwatering can physically damage the roots, preventing them from absorbing *any* nutrients. Additionally, overly compacted soil can restrict proper air and water movement, leading to nutrient uptake issues by starving the roots of oxygen.",
      "source": "target",
